90" data-id="1656408976790"><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1657501771011" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1657501771011"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>You've probably already researched this matter and tried relying on more aggressive knurling on your barbell or dumbells. You may have even tried using chalk or <a href="https://torokhtiy.com/blogs/reviews/best-liquid-chalk-for-lifting" class="" target="_blank">liquid chalk</a>. Try using some gloves to improve your grip during deadlifts. And yet, here you are, still wondering how to improve grip strength for deadlift.</p><p>There's a reason for that. Sometimes, you have to physically improve the grip of your hand. And until you do that, no outside help will do the trick. Then can boost your grip, but not replace what you are currently lacking.</p><p>In this article, you'll learn all there is to know about improving your deadlift grip and achieving your goal realistically and effectively.</p><p>Let's not beat around the bush for too long and jump straight to the point!</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1677509396432" class="gf_row" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1677509396432" data-extraclass=""><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1657094583441" data-id="1657094583441"><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1677509396372" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1677509396372"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><strong>The question ‘How to improve grip strength for deadlift‘ can be summarized to involve regular targeted exercises such as farmer's walks, plate pinches, and static holds. Incorporate grip-enhancing tools like fat grips or grip strengtheners into your routine. Limiting lifting straps can force your grip to work harder and adapt, further boosting its strength.</strong></p></div></div></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1659069737862" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1659069737862" data-resolution="3000x3000" style=""><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/2982a8e7-f36d-40b5-8593-23ac4214a948/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/WBCM-How-to-improve-grip-strength-for-deadlift.png" alt="WBCM How to Improve Grip Strength for Deadlift?" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="615" data-width="1000px" data-height="auto" title="WBCM How to Improve Grip Strength for Deadlift?" natural-width="1200" natural-height="615"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1670485569813" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1670485569813"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">What Types of Grips Are There in the Deadlift?</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1676126586293" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1676126586293" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>In the realm of <a href="https://www.stack.com/a/deadlift-grip/" class="" target="_blank">deadlifting, weightlifters mainly use three types of grips</a>: the double overhand grip, the mixed grip, and the hook grip.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1675081935903" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1675081935903"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Double Overhand Grip</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685254732275" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1685254732275" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>This is the most common and straightforward grip where both palms face the lifter. It's a great starting point for beginners as it evenly distributes the load across both arms. If you've ever done a deadlift or have seen anyone perform one - this is the grip that was most likely used.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685346719821" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1685346719821" data-resolution="3000x3000" style=""><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/c2c536b6-0710-40d2-acea-918da005ecb0/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/WBCM-Double-Overhand-Grip-deadlifting.jpg" alt="WBCM Double Overhand Grip Deadlifting" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="750" height="532" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="WBCM Double Overhand Grip Deadlifting" natural-width="750" natural-height="532"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685278081541" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1685278081541"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Mixed Grip</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685278083404" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1685278083404" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>One palm faces the lifter (supine), and the other faces away (prone). This grip provides a better hold on the barbell, reducing the chance of the bar rolling out of your hands. However, it could lead to imbalances over time due to the asymmetrical nature of the grip. You'll constantly have to switch your supine and prone hands to avoid the imbalance that may occur if ignored.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685346954587" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1685346954587" data-resolution="3000x3000" style=""><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/aa5a2a76-8f19-4f3c-87ed-d360e52e286e/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/WBCM-Mixed-grip-deadlifting.jpg" alt="WBCM Mixed Grip Deadlifting" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="954" height="636" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="WBCM Mixed Grip Deadlifting" natural-width="954" natural-height="636"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685346641869" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1685346641869"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Hook Grip</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685346645024" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1685346645024" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>This advanced grip technique traps the thumb between the bar and the first two fingers. It's notoriously uncomfortable but offers a secure grip, making it a favorite among Olympic and powerlifters. This grip helps mitigate the risk of imbalances associated with the mixed grip at the cost of comfort. You'll have to decide how much you prefer security over convenience while doing deadlifting.</p><p>Each grip has advantages and challenges, so choosing the one that best suits your lifting style, goals, comfort level, and safety is crucial. Also, if you are unfamiliar with any of these or do not use them regularly, consider or start using different grips for your deadlift session. Not just to spice things up, but to see if any of these better suit your body and form.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1684916982418" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1684916982418" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/4830638e-5217-4ee8-9d51-fe86d0506283/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/WBCM-Hook-grip.jpg" alt="WBCM Hook Grip Deadlift" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1920" height="1280" data-width="auto" data-height="auto" title="WBCM Hook Grip Deadlift" natural-width="1920" natural-height="1280"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1678538705792" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1678538705792"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Why Is Strong Grip Important in Deadlift?</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1683878698422" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1683878698422" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p></p><div>The benefits of having a firm grip might be obvious if you’re a rock climber. But what about deadlifting? You might think a deadlift is all about squeezing your buttocks, keeping a proper form, and using your back to lift. Well, no. Not really. The grip is one of the more critical factors in a deadlift, but people only notice that once they start increasing the weight load during their deadlift exercises.</div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685276059274" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1685276059274"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Stability And Control</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685347247388" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1685347247388" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p></p><div>A firm grip gives you better control over the barbell, reducing its chances of wobbling or slipping out of your hands. This increases the safety and effectiveness of your lifts.</div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685278129379" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1685278129379"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Increased Lifting Capacity</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685278130961" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1685278130961" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p></p><div>Your grip strength can often be the bottleneck in your deadlift performance. With a stronger grip, you can hold and lift heavier weights, leading to more significant strength and muscle gains.</div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685278170571" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1685278170571"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Improved Form</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685278171938" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1685278171938" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p></p><div>A solid grip helps maintain proper form during deadlifts. When you can grip the barbell firmly, keeping your back straight and performing the lift correctly becomes easier, minimizing the risk of injury.</div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685278188264" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1685278188264"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Endurance</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685278189749" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1685278189749" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p></p><div>The stronger your grip, the longer you can hold onto the barbell. This can significantly improve your endurance during sets, allowing you to perform more reps, leading to enhanced muscle growth and strength.</div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Liquid" data-key="liquid" data-atomgroup="module" id="m-1683886340962" class="module-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-liquid" data-ver="1.1" data-id="1683886340962" data-name="Right click on this, and choose Edit Code."><div class="module gf_module- gf_module--lg gf_module--md gf_module--sm gf_module--xs {{extraClass}}"><!-- Begin Mailchimp Signup Form --><style>.evg-mail-form h3 {margin-top: 0;}.evg-mail-form {margin: 50px 0;border-radius: 7px;border: 1px solid #bbbbbb;padding: 22px;padding-right: 50px;position: relative;font-family: Montserrat,sans-serif;}.evg-mail-form__grid {display: grid;grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;align-items: center;gap: 50px;}.evg-mail-form__image {max-width: 100%;border-radius: 7px;}.evg-mail-form__inputs {display: grid;grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr;gap: 15px 10px;}.evg-mail-form__inputs #mce-responses {grid-column: 1/4;}.evg-mail-form__inputs input {width: 100%;box-sizing: border-box;font-size: 17px;padding: 10px 10px;border: 1px solid #bbb;outline: none;box-shadow: none;background-color: white;font-weight: 400;font-family: Montserrat,sans-serif;}.evg-mail-form__inputs input.mce_inline_error {border-color: red !important;}.evg-mail-form__inputs input[type="submit"] {text-transform: uppercase;background-color: #ef0404;color: white;border: none;outline: none;box-shadow: none;cursor: pointer;font-weight: 700;border-radius: 5px;font-family: Montserrat,sans-serif;}.evg-mail-form__checkbox {display: grid;grid-templa